03:08.474 --> 03:23.074
It was my good fortune to be at Woods Hole from 
August 1941

03:08.474 --> 03:23.074
until February 1942 as a civilian. I then went into 
the Navy as a specialist officer in charge of bathy

03:23.763 --> 03:30.490
thermographs. While at Woods Hole, I had the 
pleasure of working with Alfred Woodcock, who was

03:32.211 --> 03:53.432
the first bathy thermograph observer on the 
Atlantis, and Morris Ewing's brother, John

03:32.211 --> 03:53.432
Ewing, a boy named Rusty Tyro, I think it was, 
Tyrus. from Texas and myself for bathy

03:53.547 --> 04:13.410
thermograph observers on the second cruise for 
bathy thermograph observations across the Gulf

03:53.547 --> 04:13.410
Stream and in the mixing area east of Nova Scotia in 
September and October 1941. The first class of ten

04:13.490 --> 04:23.301
engines each were sent to Woods Hole for training 
and graduated before Pearl Harbor. I can remember

04:26.742 --> 04:41.980
with considerable nostalgia the 
you-take-this-one-I-take-that-one method by

04:26.742 --> 04:41.980
which the boys determined which ocean they would 
go into without any realization of what was ahead

04:26.742 --> 04:41.980
for them. In February of 1942, I joined the Navy. I 
was assigned to bureau of ships in the sonar design

04:47.527 --> 04:51.972
section. The head of this section was then a 
commander by the name of Rawson Bennett II. He

04:59.371 --> 05:06.901
later became Rear Admiral Rawson Bennett and was 
Chief of Naval Research when he retired or shortly

04:59.371 --> 05:06.901
thereafter.

05:09.464 --> 05:15.512
On this man and on the fact that Roger Revelle came 
in from Scripps, in November of 42 hangs more

05:15.863 --> 05:24.232
oceanography than history will probably ever be 
able to record.

05:27.136 --> 05:41.451
I have given to Dr. Calvert a copy of a memorandum 
for file written by Rawson Bennett called

05:27.136 --> 05:41.451
Oceanography in the Bureau of Ships, dictated in 
1953 after it was all over. I stayed in the Bureau of

05:43.574 --> 05:45.516
Ships from February 1942 until October of that 
year, during which times the beginnings of the

05:45.901 --> 06:05.689
many large contracts for bathy thermograph 
procurement were initiated, and I was in charge of

05:45.901 --> 06:05.689
riding herd on those contracts until I left the 
Bureau in October. The Bristol Company at

06:07.471 --> 06:10.255
Waterbury, Connecticut made the best ones and the 
first ones, although the patent was held by the

06:10.302 --> 06:21.510
Submarine Signal Company and it was necessary to 
buy 500 bathy thermographs from them. although

06:22.283 --> 06:30.672
they did very little of the actual technical parts 
of the instrument, just finishing the brass

06:22.283 --> 06:30.672
casings. But in that way, the patent costs and 
royalties were settled. And the Bristol Company

06:35.678 --> 06:45.649
put out the bathyr thermographs, which had been 
handmade up to that time by Allen Vine, Morris

06:35.678 --> 06:45.649
Ewing, and so on. If you will turn to a paper given In 
October 1970, at the Silver Jubilee of the

06:50.920 --> 07:09.984
Instrument Society of America, paper number 
735-70,

06:50.920 --> 07:09.984
The Mechanical Bathymograph and Historical 
Review, by B.K. Cooper and Eugene C. LaFond, a good

07:10.004 --> 07:18.835
part of the story of the early development of the 
instrument will be taken care of. This paper and

07:20.738 --> 07:38.106
Bennett's paper lay the background for a 
coincidence, a fortunate coincidence, on which

07:20.738 --> 07:38.106
the oceanographers have hung many a project. It 
was the fact that a Navy need, that is, something to

07:39.508 --> 07:46.780
help anti-submarine warfare, was met by a 
mechanical device that the scientists had

07:48.194 --> 07:59.626
developed to give an indication of the structure 
of the upper layers of the sea temperature-wise.

08:02.909 --> 08:12.919
This little piece of brass, which the scientists 
could give to a naval officer and say, this will

08:02.909 --> 08:12.919
help you in your war, opened the floodgates of 
funding and the Navy was able, through Beership's

08:13.928 --> 08:32.771
support, to carry out with the scientists the 
recommendations of the Coal Pits Committee that

08:13.928 --> 08:32.771
if the Navy wished to improve their 
anti-submarine warfare detection

08:13.928 --> 08:32.771
capabilities, they should learn all they could 
about the ocean. It was almost a carte blanche as

08:34.133 --> 08:38.318
far as projects were concerned. And during the 
patriotic periods of the war, People from all

08:43.882 --> 08:53.193
walks of life were dragged in or came in willingly 
to be a part of the big anti-submarine warfare

08:43.882 --> 08:53.193
effort. It is of interest that Lyman Spitzer, the 
well-known astronomer, for instance, wrote the

08:54.875 --> 09:06.329
first bathy thermograph instruction manual.

09:08.932 --> 09:12.336
Many famous names in other lines of biology 
geology, and other sciences today worked with the

09:13.058 --> 09:22.213
anti-submarine warfare group during the war 
wholeheartedly. And from their connection, as

09:23.335 --> 09:35.995
the years came on later, the oceanography devices 
and instruments of today developed as almost

09:23.335 --> 09:35.995
linear descendants of the work of these people. In 
addition to the fortunate coincidence of a need

09:38.540 --> 09:55.448
and an instrument to fill it, there came together, 
in November of 1942, Roger Revell from Scripps

09:38.540 --> 09:55.448
Institution of Oceanography and Rawson Bennett 
in the Bureau of Ships. Roger had direct orders to

09:57.010 --> 10:01.037
the Hydrographic Office. but with his usual 
wonderful ability to sense where the power lay, he

10:01.152 --> 10:09.984
had additional orders to the Bureau of Ships. And 
the old story is that he used to work all day in the

10:10.004 --> 10:30.231
Bureau of Ships, then go to the Cosmos Club, sit 
down with Mary Sears, who was a wave on duty at the

10:10.004 --> 10:30.231
Hydrographic Office as a lieutenant commander, 
and he would lay out for her the work that should be

10:10.004 --> 10:30.231
done in the charting and the hydrographic areas 
and the study of hydrographic stations at

10:30.582 --> 10:48.207
hydrographic office and at 11 o'clock after 
supper and with her instructions she would go home

10:30.582 --> 10:48.207
to carry out his part of the work at the 
hydrographic office until the next meeting. It

10:48.227 --> 10:51.392
was a labor of love on both parts and worked 
beautifully. Roger's immense grasp of the

10:52.604 --> 11:14.916
situation, both for anti-submarine warfare and 
his innate talent for being able to tell a naval

10:52.604 --> 11:14.916
officer the kinds of work a scientist could do for 
him to help him, plus the fact that Rawson Bennett

10:52.604 --> 11:14.916
was a graduate not only of the Naval Academy, but 
also of the University of California and could

11:15.267 --> 11:25.920
talk to a scientist in mathematical terms on his 
own level made it a very wonderful combination.

11:26.841 --> 11:37.694
And this combination, in general, held right 
straight on through Bikini when Roger left Joint

11:26.841 --> 11:37.694
Task Force One to return to Scripps. It must be 
remembered that a war was going on, ships were

11:41.339 --> 11:54.732
being sunk off the coast at the rate of four and five 
a night, and the scientists as well as the naval

11:41.339 --> 11:54.732
officers had one aim in common. This did not, 
however, prevent fundamental research from

11:54.752 --> 12:00.297
going on to accomplish that problem. There used to 
be, in the old days of the Navy contracts, a clause

12:01.499 --> 12:08.005
which permitted the person at work to go back as far 
as necessary in fundamentals to attain what was

12:08.069 --> 12:15.159
needed. And if there was no fundamental, he could 
go back and try to establish it. And on this general

12:23.651 --> 12:32.243
principle hung a great deal of the basic research 
that was difficult for the naval people later on to

12:23.651 --> 12:32.243
understand. But during the war, it was all The 
scientists were serving human purposes, just

12:35.947 --> 12:50.421
like Spitzer did in writing that manual, far below 
their capabilities in one sense, but were getting

12:35.947 --> 12:50.421
a broadened outlook as to what could be done. And 
the money was carried on. It even carried on after

12:54.364 --> 13:04.654
the letdown, after World War II, because then came 
Korea, and again the gates were opened, for

13:05.005 --> 13:06.227
additional funding. And it was only far later on 
when the Mayfield Amendment came up in which they

13:07.288 --> 13:23.970
said everything had to be relevant to a stated Navy 
need that the then operating Office of Research

13:07.288 --> 13:23.970
had to begin to curtail its activities. It is 
interesting to note and sometimes not so amusing

13:25.432 --> 13:34.084
to the Office of Naval Research people than whom 
there are no finer and to whom all honor should be

13:34.553 --> 13:59.245
due for the research that has gone on in the ocean, 
that the Bureau of Ships preceded the Office of

13:34.553 --> 13:59.245
Naval Research in the general area and did the 
funding of the contracts which the Office of Naval

13:34.553 --> 13:59.245
Research later took over with Scripps, with Woods 
Hole, and with Lamont Geological Observatory,

13:34.553 --> 13:59.245
Columbia University, and so on. It irks the ONR 
people when I say, from beer ships, before ONR, we

14:00.828 --> 14:07.484
are. But to some extent, and to a large extent, in 
fact, during the war, it was absolutely true.

14:15.830 --> 14:24.743
former assistant secretary of the Navy, has given 
a charming description in one of his papers of the

14:15.830 --> 14:24.743
formation of ONR and has a lieutenant commander. 
He thought there should be an assistant secretary

14:25.084 --> 14:34.518
of the Navy for research, which came about with him 
as a first incumbent after the war.

14:37.703 --> 14:43.592
But going back again, it was the coincidence of two 
brains, Ravel and Bennett, who could talk to each

14:44.230 --> 14:52.478
other, Bennett, who could give him the official 
go-ahead, and the wherewithal, Roger, who could

14:44.230 --> 14:52.478
see the need and apply it. Believe it or not, out of 
that section came such things as the only really

14:53.919 --> 15:13.697
good defense against the kamikaze, and that were 
the smoke pots that Roger had installed on the rear

14:53.919 --> 15:13.697
of the ships, which could, under certain wind 
conditions, could obscure the ship and help

14:53.919 --> 15:13.697
divert the aim of the terrible kamikaze. That was 
just one thing out of the realm of oceanography

15:16.933 --> 15:20.639
that he was interested in. And the scope of his 
interest ran from the bottom of the ocean to the top

15:20.699 --> 15:27.011
of space. And he was as much in meteorology as he was 
in oceanography in certain phases. Another group

15:34.383 --> 15:47.745
that must be given their proper place are the 30 
engines that were trained at Woods Hole, given one

15:34.383 --> 15:47.745
bath of thermograph, a spool of wire, and a little 
winch, and sent out to teach the admirals about

15:34.383 --> 15:47.745
oceanography. Well, it didn't work very often, 
and these boys were often and always incorporated

15:48.646 --> 15:55.277
into the ship's company. And because they were 
good officers, they made splendid records. One of

15:59.119 --> 16:00.681
them received the Navy Cross. Many died, several 
died in the line of duty. And their record is second

16:05.446 --> 16:09.670
to none as a group. They did teach a great many naval 
officers at least how to say bathymograph and

16:09.691 --> 16:15.297
oceanography.

16:19.982 --> 16:24.707
Union's development of the submarine 
bathymograph, as recorded in the paper, and from

16:25.261 --> 16:36.556
his own write-up of it, was the most important 
thing in that there was a positive use that could be

16:25.261 --> 16:36.556
made rather than an interpretation after the 
fact. There was a positive use that could be made of

16:36.796 --> 16:44.546
the instrument, and it was made by the 
submariners, and it was welcomed by a great many of

16:36.796 --> 16:44.546
them.

16:47.470 --> 16:49.733
In the Pacific, at least, the success of the of the 
program, which was carried out personally by Alan

16:51.029 --> 17:18.977
Vine at the submarine headquarters at Pearl 
Harbor, was that Joe Grenfell, later Vice Admiral

16:51.029 --> 17:18.977
Grenfell, who at that time was operations officer 
for Submarines Pacific under Admiral Lockwood,

16:51.029 --> 17:18.977
Joe Grenfell would put on his summary of the cruise 
report of the returning submarines a little

16:51.029 --> 17:18.977
phrase like, The use of the Bathy thermograph was 
noted with approval, which made all the submarine

17:19.902 --> 17:33.137
skippers who got copies of their brothers' 
reports see what is this instrument and treat it

17:19.902 --> 17:33.137
with much more respect. Little things of this kind 
were important in those days where things were

17:34.819 --> 17:42.348
coming so fast. Among the people who were 
important in the Pacific was Captain T.W. Rogers,

17:48.284 --> 18:12.707
now retired, at Kanawha Street in Washington, 
D.C., who was in charge of the Special Electronics

17:48.284 --> 18:12.707
Section of the Maintenance

17:48.284 --> 18:12.707
Correction, who was in charge of the Electronics 
Division of the Service Force Pacific Fleet, his

17:48.284 --> 18:12.707
special job being to personally, with his 
assistance, approve the installation of

18:12.890 --> 18:22.380
electronic equipment so that the fighting ships 
got their equipment first rather than having it

18:12.890 --> 18:22.380
wasted on coastal vessels. Under him, I went out as 
a specialist officer in charge of the BT

18:24.022 --> 18:37.557
installation program in the Pacific and was given 
charge of about six officers on the ships in the

18:24.022 --> 18:37.557
Pacific fleet. These men worked all the way from 
Alaska to Australia and as I mentioned, were Woods

18:43.720 --> 18:49.870
Hole train engines and they did a superb job.

18:52.855 --> 19:09.441
I stayed on in the Navy one more year until 1946 and 
was able to assist in the preparations and the

18:52.855 --> 19:09.441
passage of the oceanographers and the baggage and 
all of that group on their way to Bikini for the

18:52.855 --> 19:09.441
great atom bomb test. was one important point in 
connection with the procurement of bathy

