thermographs in any quantity it was not 
considered by the navy to be a scientific

19:11.294 --> 19:41.233
instrument it was considered to be a component 
that is a part a necessary part of a sonar equipment

19:11.294 --> 19:41.233
just as a light bulb would be to do a particular 
function and on that basis mass procurement was

19:11.294 --> 19:41.233
possible and of course after the war these Those 
that were left over were used for scientific

19:41.872 --> 19:44.875
purposes. And during the war, as you can see if you 
turn to the back of the Bathie Thermograph paper,

19:45.716 --> 19:56.065
you could almost plot the progress of the war by the 
Bathie Thermograph observations. There was one I

19:57.146 --> 19:59.769
was very proud to see later at Scripps. It was 500 
miles from Tokyo, and it was in 1942. And it was on

20:05.494 --> 20:11.440
one of the ships of Doolittle's Tokyo raid.

20:14.542 --> 20:26.645
But however you make a distinction between a 
useful tool and an instrument,

20:14.542 --> 20:26.645
the distinction was important to the 
oceanographers. And as time went on after 1948,

20:27.787 --> 20:32.095
the more basic part of the research and 
development was taken over by the Office of Naval

20:32.446 --> 20:49.105
Research and the applied research on which we 
could at least foresee a Navy payoff was kept in the

20:32.446 --> 20:49.105
Bureau of Ships where possible.

20:51.968 --> 21:00.138
I've always thought the Bureau of Ships should 
have kept the Marine Physical Laboratory at La

20:51.968 --> 21:00.138
Jolla. It was set up by Bennett and his Admiral at 
that time in order that there should be a feed

21:02.348 --> 21:12.762
direct to the bureauships of the scientific minds 
of the community. On that basis, three professors

21:13.643 --> 21:19.591
were paid by the University of California, not the 
Navy. They were Carl Eckert, Russell Raitt, and

21:20.332 --> 21:25.659
Leonard Lieberman. These were four professors of 
the University of California. Yet they were

21:31.019 --> 21:42.113
assigned to the Marine Physical Laboratory, for 
which the facilities and the operation and the

21:31.019 --> 21:42.113
equipment were furnished by the Navy. And they 
were stationed deliberately on the grounds of the

21:43.855 --> 21:56.791
then Electronics Laboratory, Navy Electronics 
Laboratory at Point Loma, for this close

21:43.855 --> 21:56.791
collaboration in electronics and in instrument 
development. When the Office of Naval Research

21:57.913 --> 21:59.895
took it over, They were probably on more basic 
programs. But at the same time, the information

22:05.469 --> 22:11.317
had to be filtered through one more agency before 
it got to the Bureau of Ships. However, the way at

22:12.058 --> 22:29.342
that time that this was done, about 1950, was to 
move the instrument groups and the hardware

22:12.058 --> 22:29.342
groups, as the Navy liked to call them,

22:29.947 --> 22:36.393
to the bureauships and the theoreticians and the 
research groups to ONR. I have no real quarrel with

22:37.334 --> 22:42.739
that decision, though I hate to see MPL leave the 
bureauships. So the bureauships program

22:43.580 --> 22:59.194
gradually dwindled on down until it became about a 
$3 million, $3 to $4 million program, but at its

22:43.580 --> 22:59.194
best perhaps in many ways because the Navy 
laboratories themselves under that program were

23:00.018 --> 23:08.309
given a measure of freedom for basic research, 
sometimes equal to that which the Naval Research

23:00.018 --> 23:08.309
Laboratory itself could provide. I used to argue 
with the naval officers and the appropriation

23:09.651 --> 23:23.530
persons that under any contract, at least 30% of 
the funds should go for basic research to support

23:09.651 --> 23:23.530
the projects which were named in hardware. And 
they were very generous most of the time. Also, by

23:28.182 --> 23:56.738
taking advantage of funds that had been unused by 
different departments and the bureauships, in

23:28.182 --> 23:56.738
the early days it was possible to get chunks of 
money from the oceanographers at the Navy

23:28.182 --> 23:56.738
laboratories because we could say it was ready to 
be spent at any time, whereas if you had to go out to a

23:28.182 --> 23:56.738
contractor, we would not be able to appropriate to 
contract the money to be spent within the time

23:28.182 --> 23:56.738
limit before the appropriation ran out. It was 
always enjoyable to see the way that the people at

23:58.304 --> 24:06.855
the Navy Electronics Laboratory Oceanographic 
Section in those days used such chunks of money.

